    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "From a material science perspective, a high-density, tightly woven structure creates a torturous pathway for penetrants like liquids, gases, or particulate matter. Each thread intersection (the weave structure) acts as a physical barrier, forcing any substance attempting to pass through to repeatedly navigate around solid fiber crossings. This increased number of barriers per unit area dramatically reduces the mean free path, making penetration significantly more difficult than in a loosely woven material.",
